              <h2>How math conversions work (the factor‑label method)</h2>
              <p>
                All unit conversions are based on
                <strong>equivalent ratios</strong>. For example:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>1 inch = 2.54 centimeters</li>
                <li>1 hour = 60 minutes</li>
                <li>1 kilogram = 1000 grams</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If two quantities are equal, their ratio is 1. That means both
                \(\dfrac{1\ \text{in}}{2.54\ \text{cm}}\) and \(\dfrac{2.54\
                \text{cm}}{1\ \text{in}}\) are equal to 1.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">General conversion formula</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{New value} = \text{Old value} \times
                  \frac{\text{Target unit}}{\text{Original unit}} \]
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                  Choose the fraction so that the original unit cancels and the
                  target unit remains.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example 1 – Converting 5 kilometers to meters</h3>
              <p>We know that 1 km = 1000 m, so:</p>
              <p>
                \[ 5\ \text{km} \times \frac{1000\ \text{m}}{1\ \text{km}} =
                5000\ \text{m} \]
              </p>
              <p>The “km” units cancel, leaving meters.</p>

              <h3>
                Example 2 – Multi‑step conversion: 50 miles per hour to meters
                per second
              </h3>
              <p>We will use three facts:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>1 mile = 1609.34 m</li>
                <li>1 hour = 60 minutes</li>
                <li>1 minute = 60 seconds</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                \[ 50\ \frac{\text{mi}}{\text{h}} \times \frac{1609.34\
                \text{m}}{1\ \text{mi}} \times \frac{1\ \text{h}}{60\
                \text{min}} \times \frac{1\ \text{min}}{60\ \text{s}} \approx
                22.35\ \frac{\text{m}}{\text{s}} \]
              </p>
              <p>
                Notice how miles and hours cancel out step by step, leaving
                meters per second. The calculator’s “Show steps” feature uses
                exactly this approach.
              </p>

              <h2>Supported math conversion categories</h2>
              <h3>1. Length</h3>
              <p>
                Convert between metric and imperial length units commonly used
                in school math, science, and everyday life:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Metric:</strong> millimeters (mm), centimeters (cm),
                  meters (m), kilometers (km)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Imperial/US:</strong> inches (in), feet (ft), yards
                  (yd), miles (mi)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                Example: 1 inch = 2.54 cm, 1 mile = 5280 ft, 1 km = 1000 m.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Area</h3>
              <p>Useful for geometry, land area, and floor plans:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>mm², cm², m², km²</li>
                <li>in², ft², yd², acres</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Remember that area conversions square the length factor: if 1 ft
                = 0.3048 m, then 1 ft² = (0.3048 m)² ≈ 0.092903 m².
              </p>

              <h3>3. Volume</h3>
              <p>Common in science labs and cooking:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>mL, L, m³</li>
                <li>tsp, tbsp, cups, fl oz, pints, quarts, gallons (US)</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                Example: 1 L = 1000 mL, 1 US gallon ≈ 3.78541 L.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Weight / Mass</h3>
              <p>For physics, chemistry, and everyday measurements:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>mg, g, kg, metric tons</li>
                <li>oz, lb, short ton (US)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Example: 1 kg ≈ 2.20462 lb, 1 lb = 16 oz.</p>

              <h3>5. Temperature</h3>
              <p>
                Temperature conversions are slightly different because they
                involve both a scale and an offset.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Celsius (°C)</li>
                <li>Fahrenheit (°F)</li>
                <li>Kelvin (K)</li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Key temperature formulas</p>
                <p>\( ^\circ F = \dfrac{9}{5} \, ^\circ C + 32 \)</p>
                <p>\( ^\circ C = \dfrac{5}{9} (^\circ F - 32) \)</p>
                <p>\( K = ^\circ C + 273.15 \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>6. Time</h3>
              <p>Basic time conversions used in word problems and physics:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>seconds, minutes, hours, days</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>7. Speed</h3>
              <p>Combines length and time units:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>m/s, km/h</li>
                <li>mph (miles per hour)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Example: 1 m/s = 3.6 km/h, 60 mph ≈ 96.56 km/h.</p>

              <h2>How to use this math conversions tool effectively</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose the category</strong> that matches your problem
                  (for example Length or Temperature).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the value</strong> you want to convert in the
                  “Value” box.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Select the From and To units</strong> from the
                  dropdowns.
                </li>
                <li>Click <strong>Convert</strong> to see the result.</li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Show steps</strong> to view the
                  dimensional‑analysis setup and each step of the calculation.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                For exam practice (SAT, nursing math, etc.), try solving the
                problem by hand first, then use this calculator to check both
                your answer and your method.
              </p>

              <h2>
                Common mistakes in unit conversions (and how to avoid them)
              </h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Forgetting to square or cube factors</strong> when
                  converting area or volume.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Using the wrong direction</strong> of a conversion
                  factor (for example multiplying by 2.54 instead of dividing).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Dropping units</strong> in intermediate steps, which
                  makes it hard to see errors.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mixing up temperature formulas</strong> by forgetting
                  the +32 or −32.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Writing out units and using the factor‑label method, as shown in
                the steps panel, eliminates most of these errors.
              </p>

